    <item>
      <title>Re: Cleric Stigmas</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=clericbalance&amp;message.id=8317#M8317</link>
      <description>It depends what you mean by stigma.  You could not have a 1.5 and be a very skilled player.  However, if I see someone without a 1.5, I will generally assume their gear is not that great, and it will make me less likely to choose them for an XP group, simply because better gear makes XP groups go more smoothly.  Gear is not everything either.  I've met well geared clerics that suck, and poorly geared clerics that do a lot with what they have, but all else being equal, if I have a choice, I'll take the guy with better gear, especially items like a 1.5.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;As for people applying to my guild, we are an endgame guild, and do not demand a 1.5.  If we see one, it's a plus, but it's by no means necessary.  You are correct in that even a 1.5 is very hard to do guildless, and a 2.0 is nearly impossible, anguish orb aside.  We do expect applicants to work on their 1.5's, and have gotten 1.5's for all but one of our cleric apps atm, and he is currently working on it.  We do expect apps to have decent gear.  This doesn't mean anguish level, but if we see apps wearing 40/40 bracers, bp's, legs, etc., or using ldon 6 to a resist augments, we tell them to get better gear and come back.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Sometimes, no matter how skilled you are, lack of gear will make you unable to do your job.  This is only in the harder content though.  8K is a pretty decent manapool, and if you have a lot of AA's, I would think RSS wouldn't be a big problem.  I certainly healed in RSS before I had my shield clicky.  At the same time though, sometimes the clicky will save you, so you have to expect people to prefer those that have it when looking for people to xp with.</description>
